sections.english:
“Monks, these four things are exceedingly distant from each other. What are these four? Monks, the sky and the earth: this is the first thing that is exceedingly distant. Monks, the near shore of the ocean and its far shore: this is the second thing that is exceedingly distant. Monks, where the illuminator, the sun, rises and where it sets: this is the third thing that is exceedingly distant. Monks, the Dhamma of the good and the Dhamma of the bad: this is the fourth thing that is exceedingly distant. Indeed, monks, these are the four things that are exceedingly distant.”

Far is the sky, far is the earth;
They say the far shore of the ocean is far.
Where the sun, the illuminator, rises,
And where it sets;
But farther than that, they truly say,
Are the Dhamma of the good and the Dhamma of the bad.

The association with the good is unwavering;
However long it endures, it remains the same.
But the association with the bad quickly fades away;
Therefore, the Dhamma of the good is far from the unvirtuous.

At one time, the Blessed One was dwelling in Savatthi, in Jeta’s Grove, Anathapindika’s monastery. Now at that time, the venerable Visakha Pañcalaputta was instructing, rousing, inspiring, and gladdening the bhikkhus in the service hall with a Dhamma talk, using a popular, clear, articulate, meaningful, well-expressed, and unattached speech. Then the Blessed One, having emerged from his seclusion in the evening, approached the service hall. Having approached, he sat down on the seat that had been prepared. Having sat down, the Blessed One addressed the bhikkhus: “Who, bhikkhus, in the service hall, is instructing, rousing, inspiring, and gladdening the bhikkhus with a Dhamma talk, using a popular, clear, articulate, meaningful, well-expressed, and unattached speech?” “Venerable sir, it is the venerable Visakha Pañcalaputta who is instructing, rousing, inspiring, and gladdening the bhikkhus in the service hall with a Dhamma talk, using a popular, clear, articulate, meaningful, well-expressed, and unattached speech.” Then the Blessed One said to the venerable Visakha Pañcalaputta: “Excellent, excellent, Visakha! Truly, Visakha, you instruct, rouse, inspire, and gladden the bhikkhus with a Dhamma talk, using a popular, clear, articulate, meaningful, well-expressed, and unattached speech.”

As long as a wise person does not speak, they do not recognize them among the fools;
But when they speak, proclaiming the deathless state, they do recognize them.
Let one speak, let one illuminate the Dhamma, let one uphold the banner of the sages;
The sages have well-spoken words as their banner, for truly, the Dhamma is the banner of the sages.
